can you do this ? Cloud Firestore automatically creates collections (and even documents!) the very first time you add data to a specific path. It's like magic!
Let's say you want to add a document about a user to a collection called users . If the users collection doesn't exist yet, when you write the user document to that path using the Firebase SDK in your web app, Cloud Firestore will automatically create the users collection for you.
Hereâ€™s a little taste of how you might do that in TypeScript/JavaScript:
import { getFirestore, collection, addDoc } from 'firebase/firestore';
import { app } from './firebase-config'; // Assuming you have your Firebase app initialized here

const db = getFirestore(app);

async function createUser(userId: string, name: string, email: string) {
  try {
    // This is the path: 'users' collection
    const docRef = await addDoc(collection(db, 'users'), {
      userId: userId,
      name: name,
      email: email,
      createdAt: new Date()
    });
    console.log("Document written with ID: ", docRef.id);
    // If the 'users' collection didn't exist, it's created now!

  } catch (e) {
    console.error("Error adding document: ", e);
  }
}

// Call the function to create a user (and the 'users' collection if it's new)
createUser('user123', 'Ada Lovelace', 'ada.lovelace@example.com');
 Expand 
In this example, the line addDoc(collection(db, 'users'), { ... }) tells Firestore to add a new document to the users collection. If users wasn't there before, poof ! It comes into existence automatically the moment this code successfully writes a document to it.
So, you don't need a separate tool to "connect and create collections automatically." The connection happens via the Firebase SDK when your app initializes and interacts with the database, and the creation of collections happens automatically as you add documents to them for the first time using your code.
While this automatic creation is super convenient for getting started, as you build your app, you'll want to think carefully about how you structure your data (your collections and documents) to make querying and managing your data efficient.
Hope this clears things up! Let me know if you have more questions about structuring your data or using the SDK.

